value.value: Fin ray that is composed of elastoidin, unmineralized, and unsegmented.
Fin ray found in dipnoans that are composed of a superficial region of acellular fibrous bone, and a deep, mostly unmineralized, zone (Géraudie and Meunier 1982).

definition.value: From Witten & Huysseune (2007): 'Two zones have been recognized in these camptotrichia: a superficial region of acellular fibrous bone, and a deep, mostly unmineralized, zone (Géraudie and Meunier 1982).'

value.value: Lepidotrichium that is part of a paired fin.
Uroneurals that form the uppermost three uroneural series that overlap, and lie at an angle to, longer anterior ones.
Scale that is part of row along the midline between the dorsal fin and the back of the skull. In counting, all scales crossing the midline are included. (Fishbase) .
Median fin skeleton supporting the adipose fin.
Tubular ossifications around extension of nasal lateral line canal in fishes; typically one or two.
Soft ray that is part of the anal fin.
Soft ray that is part of the pectoral fin.
Lepidotrichium that is part of a median fin.
Fin spine that is part of a paired fin.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that is not distally branched.
Pelvic fin lepidotrichium that is not distally branched.
Anatomical cluster that consists of the hypobranchial elements within an individual.
Anatomical cluster that consists of the pharyngobranchial elements within an individual.
Anatomical cluster that consists of the basibranchial elements within an individual.
Pharyngeal arch bone immediately posterior to the ascending process, the medial surface of which articulates with the anterior end of the maxillary.

definition.value: The change from a premaxilla in which the ascending and articular processes are separate to one in which they are firmly united has occurred many times in higher teleosts. - Gosline, 1987 (Jaw Structures and Movements in Higher Teleostean Fishes)

value.value: Pharyngeal arch bone located between uncinate process of epibranchial 1 and pharyngobranchial 2.
Process of the premaxilla that extends upward, and often lies against the medial surface of the maxillary.
Pelvic fin distal radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.
